// The prelude is in scope everywhere, but it does not *own* the namespace: a program may
// declare its own `List` or `IndexError` and have that name win.
//
// This works because the prelude has a module path of its own (`Env::PRELUDE`) that
// resolution consults LAST, after every scope the caller is actually in. It used to sit
// at the root -- the program's own module path -- which made shadowing depend on how the
// prelude happened to get the name: `IndexError` (declared there) could be shadowed,
// while `List` (re-exported with `use`) could not, because prelude `use` bindings landed
// in the program's own bucket ahead of the program's own. Both spellings are exercised
// here, and both must behave the same way.
//
// The backend has to agree, and for a while it did not: it derived a type's identity and
// its runtime tag from the BARE name, so the program's `List` and the stdlib's collided
// in codegen even once the checker told them apart. Qualifying nominal identity closed
// that (docs/design/identity.md).

use std::io;

record List { junk: i64 }
record IndexError { note: str }

fn main() {
    let a = List { junk: 7 };
    io::println(to_string(a.junk));

    let b = IndexError { note: "mine" };
    io::println(b.note);
}
